04703nam a22007575i 9780812292343DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20152008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013947952  a97808122923437 a10.9783/97808122923432doi  a(DE-B1597)463550  a(OCoLC)940674406  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPS173.I6b.B455 2008eb 7aLIT0040602bisacsh04a810.9/35203922221 aBellin, Joshua David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMedicine Bundle :bIndian Sacred Performance and American Literature, 1824-1932 /cJoshua David Bellin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. George Catlin, Te-ho-pe-nee Wash-ee -- tChapter 2. Being and Becoming “Indian” -- tChapter 3. The Acts of the Prophets -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the 1820s to the 1930s, Christian missionaries and federal agents launched a continent-wide assault against Indian sacred dance, song, ceremony, and healing ritual in an attempt to transform Indian peoples into American citizens. In spite of this century-long religious persecution, Native peoples continued to perform their sacred traditions and resist the foreign religions imposed on them, as well as to develop new practices that partook of both. At the same time, some whites began to explore Indian performance with interest, and even to promote Indian sacred traditions as a source of power for their own society. The varieties of Indian performance played a formative role in American culture and identity during a critical phase in the nation's development.In Medicine Bundle, Joshua David Bellin examines the complex issues surrounding Indian sacred performance in its manifold and intimate relationships with texts and images by both Indians and whites. From the paintings of George Catlin, the traveling showman who exploited Indian ceremonies for the entertainment of white audiences, to the autobiography of Black Elk, the Lakota holy man whose long life included stints as a dancer in Buffalo Bill's Wild West show, a supplicant in the Ghost Dance movement, and a catechist in the Catholic Church, Bellin reframes American literature, culture, and identity as products of encounter with diverse performance traditions. Like the traditional medicine bundle of sacred objects bound together for ritual purposes, Indian performance and the performance of Indianness by whites and Indians alike are joined in a powerful intercultural knot.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWhite authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aIndians in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Native American.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aNative American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229234340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292343423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812292343/original  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK